{
    "analysis": "The previous Executor run loaded metric.csv and trace.csv and returned compact summaries. From that output: metric.csv contains 90,791 rows across 56 unique cmdb_id values (sample shows many db_00x entries) and covers the time range 2020-05-24 02:30:00+08 through 2020-05-24 03:30:00+08. It has 133 unique KPI names. trace.csv contains 6,240 rows across 10 unique cmdb_id values (sample shows docker_00x entries) and covers the failure interval 2020-05-24 03:00:00+08 through 2020-05-24 03:29:00+08 with 76 unique trace names. This indicates metrics include service (db_*) data across a wider time range, while traces are captured for containers (docker_*) specifically during the failure window. To follow the preprocess step, we must enumerate available components per level (service/node/pod) and enumerate the KPI and trace names so we can compute global thresholds for relevant component-KPI time series next.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Provide compact lists and counts to identify candidate components and KPIs: \n1) From metric.csv: return the count of unique cmdb_id and a breakdown of how many cmdb_ids start with each prefix (db_, os_, docker_, other). For each prefix return up to 50 sample cmdb_id names. Also return the full count of unique kpi_name and a list of all unique kpi_name values limited to 200 items (if more, return first 200 sorted alphabetically).\n2) From trace.csv: return the count of unique cmdb_id and a list of all unique cmdb_id values; return the full count of unique trace_name and a list of unique trace_name limited to 200 items (sorted alphabetically).\n3) Keep outputs compact (only counts and the requested name lists). Do not print full raw time series. Limit rows returned to the summaries above."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global P95/P05 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using full metric series, filtered metric data to the incident window (2020-05-24 03:00–03:30+08), and detected anomalies where metric values exceeded P95 or fell below P05. A compact top-affected list was returned. Observations from that result: several db_* KPIs (notably Redo_Per_Sec for db_013, db_010, db_012 and Logic_Read_Per_Sec for db_001) show high severity and multiple anomalous points at the start of the incident window (03:00–03:01). Many os_* Disk_* KPIs also show anomalies, but many disk KPI global thresholds were zero causing a sentinel severity (9999) — these require careful handling because a zero threshold can produce misleading severity numbers. The DB Redo_Per_Sec and Logic_Read_Per_Sec anomalies have large numeric deviation from their P95 thresholds (severity scores 31–77 range) and multiple anomalous points at or near 03:00, which makes them strong candidates for the root cause. To decide between service-level (db_*) and node-level (os_*) root cause and to identify the exact component and occurrence time, we should aggregate anomalies by component (cmdb_id) to see which components have the most anomalies and the earliest anomaly timestamps. This will help prioritize which components to investigate further with traces/logs. \n\nNext step: aggregate anomalies per cmdb_id to identify the predominant faulty components, earliest occurrence per component, how many distinct KPIs were affected per component, and a sample of affected KPI names. This will be a compact table (top 20) and will be saved for follow-up analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the anomalies_df stored in kernel, aggregate anomalies by cmdb_id and produce a compact top-20 table with these columns: cmdb_id, anomalies_count (total anomaly rows for this cmdb_id in the incident window), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (earliest anomaly time for this cmdb_id), unique_kpi_count (number of distinct kpi_name affected for this cmdb_id), sample_kpis (comma-separated sample of up to 10 distinct kpi_name for this cmdb_id), and max_severity (maximum severity among that cmdb_id's (cmdb_id,kpi) pairs). Sort the results by anomalies_count desc, then max_severity desc. Save the full aggregation to a kernel variable named anomalies_by_component_df and print only the top-20 rows in a compact table. Also print two small summary numbers: total distinct cmdb_id with anomalies and total anomaly rows. Keep output limited to that aggregated table and summary counts."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace anomaly detection and aggregated anomalies by component. Summary observations: many node-level components (os_019, os_017, os_020, os_018, os_022, etc.) show large numbers of anomalous KPI rows with earliest anomalies at 2020-05-24T03:00:00+08. Several DB services (db_010, db_012, db_013, db_001) show high-severity KPI anomalies (Redo_Per_Sec, Logic_Read_Per_Sec) concentrated at or just after 03:00. Trace anomalies are concentrated on docker_* containers with earliest anomalies at 03:00 as well, and severities around 1–2x. Sentinel severity values (9999) exist where P95/P05 were zero and must be treated cautiously. To pick the root cause component and exact occurrence time, we must identify the absolute earliest anomaly(s) across both metric and trace anomaly sets and inspect those records (component, KPI/trace, anomaly type, value, thresholds, severity). The earliest anomaly record(s) will indicate the first observable fault and help decide root cause level (node vs service vs container) and likely reason (e.g., heavy DB I/O if DB redo/read rates spike first, or node disk/Page-in if OS disk metrics spike first).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel anomaly tables anomalies_df (metric anomalies) and trace_anomalies_df (trace anomalies), find the absolute earliest anomaly timestamp across both tables (use the stored timestamp/datetime fields as-is). Then return a compact list (limit 20 rows) of all anomaly records that occur at that earliest timestamp, including these columns for each row: origin (value 'metric' or 'trace'), cmdb_id, kpi_name (for metric) or trace_name (for trace) as a single column 'name', timestamp, value, P95, P05, anomaly_type ('high' or 'low'), and severity (use the same severity metric as earlier). Also return a small summary: the earliest timestamp found, the total number of anomaly records at that timestamp, and the distinct components involved at that timestamp. Save the matching rows to a kernel variable named earliest_anomaly_records_df but only print the compact list and the three summary numbers."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global-threshold calculation and anomaly detection on metric and trace data, and aggregated anomalies by KPI and by component within the incident window (2020-05-24 03:00–03:30 Asia/Shanghai). Key findings so far: the absolute earliest anomalies across metrics and traces occurred at 2020-05-24T03:00:00+08. At that timestamp there are many anomaly records spanning multiple levels (db_*, docker_*, os_*). Metric anomalies at 03:00 include very large deviations in DB KPIs (for example, Redo_Per_Sec and Logic_Read_Per_Sec for several db_* components with high severity ratios: db_013, db_010, db_012, db_001, db_005 etc.). Trace anomalies are concentrated on docker_* containers with moderate severity (~1–2x). Many os_* KPIs have anomalies counts high but some have zero-derived sentinel severity values (9999) which must be treated cautiously. According to the localization rules, when multiple levels show faults, the root-cause level should be chosen by the fault that exhibits the most significant deviation from its threshold. The DB KPIs show the largest relative deviations (>> 50%), while container trace deviations are smaller and node-level results include questionable zero-threshold artifacts. Therefore DB services are the leading suspects. However, multiple db_* services are affected simultaneously at 03:00; to identify the exact root-cause component we need to rank DB services by severity and earliest anomalous KPI and inspect, per DB, the most extreme KPI (kpi_name, severity, timestamp, value). This will allow choosing a single db_* as the root cause (if one DB stands out) or indicate a broader systemic issue if multiple DBs show comparable extreme faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the metric anomaly table stored in kernel (anomalies_df), filter to DB services only (cmdb_id starting with 'db_') and produce a compact summary (save full result in kernel variable db_anomaly_summary_df). For each db_* return these columns: cmdb_id, anomalies_count (number of anomaly rows for that db in the incident window), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, unique_kpi_count (distinct KPIs anomalous), sample_kpis (up to 10 distinct KPI names comma-separated), max_severity (max severity among its KPIs). Additionally, for each db_* include the top_kpi (the KPI name with the max_severity for that db), top_kpi_severity, top_kpi_timestamp (timestamp of that KPI's earliest anomaly), and top_kpi_value (value at that earliest anomaly). Sort the output by top_kpi_severity desc then anomalies_count desc. Return only the top 10 rows in printed output and two small summary numbers: total distinct db_* components examined and number of db_* components with ≥1 anomaly. Keep outputs compact and store full table in db_anomaly_summary_df for follow-up steps."
}

